The Republican Party's strategy against Obama's re-election
Republican leaders have justified their policies by the need to combat electoral fraud.
The Brennan Center, however, describes such fraud as a myth, saying that electoral fraud is less common in the US than the number of people who die after being struck by lightning.
Republican lawyers have reported only 300 cases of electoral fraud in the U.S. over the past decade.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, these measures will partially undermine the American democratic system.
Unlike Canada, the United States is responsible for organizing federal elections.
And in this spirit, most U.S. governments have been promulgating new laws since 2009 that hamper the process of election or listing.
This phenomenon saw an upsurge after the November 2010 election, during which 675 new Republican deputies were added in 26 states.
As a result, in 2011 alone, 180 bills were submitted restricting the right to vote in 41 states.
New electoral laws require voters to present a photo ID and proof of U.S. citizenship.
In addition, these laws limit the period for early elections, invalidate the right to register on the voters' list on the day of the elections and deprive citizens with a criminal record of their right to vote.
Prior to the 2006 election, no U.S. state required voters to present a photo ID.
The first state to introduce this requirement was Indiana.
The constitutionality of Indian law was confirmed in 2008 by the Supreme Court of the United States.
The Republican authorities rushed to extend this procedure to other states.
Over the past two years, drafts of such laws have been passed in 34 states to force voters to submit photo IDs.
It should be noted that unlike Quebec, U.S. citizens do not have a universal identity card, such as a health insurance card.
In fact, 11% of U.S. citizens, i.e. 21 million people of voting age, do not own any photo ID issued by their state government office.
In addition, it does not have such an identity card for about five million new voters in 2012.
In addition, obtaining the required identity card often costs more than a hundred dollars.
The new restrictions disproportionately affect mainly young people, members of minorities and low-income people.
25% of African-Americans, 15% of people with incomes below $35,000; 18% of citizens over the age of 65 and 20% of voters between the ages of 18 and 29 therefore do not have the required photo ID.
And that's not all.
Students who are known as voters for their preference for Democratic candidates are not allowed to use their photo ID issued by their school in several states.
On the other hand, the same states allow members of hunting or fishing clubs who elect rather Republican candidates to use the cards issued by these clubs in elections.
Until 2004, no state required a proof of citizenship for elections.
The first such requirement was introduced by Arizona.
Since 2011, about 12 states have enacted laws that make it mandatory for voters to prove they are U.S. citizens.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting the number of votes from the Hispanic minority.
It should be noted that two out of three Hispanics prefer a democratic party.
In 2011, Republican lawmakers backed laws in eight states that abolished voter registration on election day.
In addition, they have restricted the right of individuals and groups to provide assistance to voters wishing to enroll.
These limitations have consequences.
For example, during the 2004 general elections, voter registration campaigns helped register about 10 million people.
However, the measures taken after 2009 caused a 17% drop in new voter enrolment in 2010 compared to 2006.
Republican lawmakers in five other states have passed laws aimed at shortening the period for early elections.
For example, during the 2008 general election in Florida, African-Americans made up 33% of voters who voted in advance, even though there were only 13% of African-American voters in that state.
It was the same with the Hispanics.
They made up only 11% of all voters, but 24% of citizens voting ahead of time.
On the other hand, whites, who represented 76% of all voters, made up only 46% of voters who voted in advance.
Democratic lawmakers and their supporters have, of course, strongly opposed the adoption of laws restricting voter registration.
Democratic governors have blocked several bills with their veto.
In order to suspend the most controversial laws, even the U.S. Attorney General intervened.
The damage was partially reduced.
For example, only 16 of the 34 states have passed laws requiring the presentation of a photo ID card.
However, the newly introduced rules will undeniably complicate the exercise of the right to vote in 2012.
Democratic critics primarily talk about the bias of the laws passed and see them as an obvious attempt to influence the results of the 2012 elections in key states.
A 2011 Brennan Center report shows that the states where these laws were passed accounted for 171 of the 270 votes in the electorate needed to win the presidential election.
It is too early to say with certainty that these legislative changes at the level of the electoral system will have a significant impact on the outcome of the presidential election in 2012.
But one thing is certain already today: these new provisions will have an adverse impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, these measures will partially undermine the American democratic system.
Detection of prostate cancer: to undergo an examination or not?
