Therefore, I recommend testing from the age of 50 or from the age of 40 if your immediate relative has prostate cancer.
Men of African American descent are also more at risk.
The key is to make the right decision once the cancer is detected.
There are aggressive types of cancer and those that are inactive.
Therefore, it is necessary to correctly explain to the patient the level of danger of his type of cancer, to offer him possible alternatives, not necessarily to treat prostate cancer, which does not have a long-term impact on life, and in these cases, rather to focus on active surveillance of the disease.
Today, many men who have been diagnosed with cancer are untreated because their type of cancer is not aggressive and does not endanger their lives.
Rather, we will suggest that they carry out active surveillance and offer them treatment in case of disease progression.
Increasingly, and with greater precision, we set criteria that help in deciding which species to treat and which not.
Nevertheless, I recommend that you take the test.
However, it is important to have an interview with a doctor and determine whether it is appropriate to undergo an examination or not.
