The Higgs Boson
The announcement of the possible discovery of the Higgs boson caused a legitimate stir last summer.
There is an opinion that this boson is involved in the mechanism that is responsible for all matter in the universe.
And then there is the last particle, the existence of which is predicted by the standard model - our best or "least bad" explanation of the nature and behavior of matter - but which has not yet been empirically observed.
Physicists are not 100% sure that it is the Higgs boson.
There is no doubt that we have a completely new particle that is very similar to the Higgs boson as predicted by the standard model.
The new data released this week at the great physics congress in Kyoto rather confirms it, but all the data are still lacking so that we can be absolutely sure.
However, let's assume it's the Higgs boson, because the risk of error seems small, and let's look at what it is.
In this world there is an absolutely indisputable law, according to which two things cannot occur at the same time in the same place.
This rule can not be circumvented - and do not try too hard, otherwise you will hurt yourself.
Although particle physics is a very strange world, it turns out that a similar law applies to it: Pauli's exclusion principle, according to which two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state" - this "state" roughly creates some of their properties.
In addition, it divides physical particles into two categories.
On the one hand, we find orderly citizens, or fermions, who obediently follow the Pauli principle.
And at the other end, there are the bosons, the mean anarchists who don’t appreciate anything at all – certainly not this principle, which means that they can be in the same place at the same time.
These bosons are further divided into two groups according to the device (by the way, absolutely amazing), which is The Particle Adventure, in the Berkeley laboratories: the mesons, which we leave here unnoticed, and the "force particles", through which great forces of nature are propagated, and with which the Higgs boson is probably somehow related.
However, it must be said that these bosons are not as exotic animals as one might think.
If you read this article, it is because of a boson with unusual banality: a photon, or "particle of light", which is the "carrier" of electromagnetic force.
When a particle with an electric charge accelerates or changes direction, it "interferes" with the electromagnetic field at that particular place, much like a pebble thrown into a pond.
From this "interference" an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared or ultraviolet radiation, etc.) arises, and this wave is nothing but a photon - and therefore one of the bosons, the "force carriers".
A more stable field
It is the same with the Higgs boson, except that it takes a different field, the Higgs field, to "disrupt" the boson.
This Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; to excite it, it is necessary to achieve very high energy values, similar to the frozen level of the pond, which only a very large boulder will become.
For this reason, it is necessary to use such a huge part accelerator as the CERN accelerator - a large hadron beam accelerator is a circle with a circumference of 27 km! - in order to develop such energy.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is again useful for clarifying the relationship between Higgs and matter.
Neither all particles nor all materials react with the electromagnetic field.
Some, for example, magnets, do so, but others do not - a piece of paper, for example, will never hold itself on the refrigerator.
And it is equally true that not all particles react with the Higgs field: those that do have a certain mass, while others (such as a photon, let's look at it) do not.
And Mrs. Nováková asks, what is all this research for, what will it “bring to us”?
From the point of view of science, it is a validation of the Standard Model (SM), which allows physicists to examine any discrepancies between observations and SM predictions.
In addition, many physicists literally want to be able to find them, because the slightest difference could open the space of "new physics" and fill some gaps in the model.
It should be noted that the model still has huge flaws, it does not bring any clarification of gravity (ouha!) or dark matter, which makes up about 80% of the cosmic mass (ouha! again).
So far, however, CERN has not found any such discrepancies.
Responses
The responses of these researches in the daily life of Mr and Mrs Novák can be very difficult to predict, but it would be a mistake to assume that there will be none.
See: In the early 1960s, the pioneers of the laser in Bell Labs had no idea of the revolution their work would bring about.
They assumed scientific use, but nothing else.
Physicist Willard Boyle - who worked at Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who created the first permanent laser beam (previous beams were pulsed) in 1962, I have already said - the laser was initially considered such a "toy for the lab".
Just imagine it...
And besides, the application can also result from all the tools that surround the research.
For example, the same Willard Boyle created a small light sensor in 1969 during his work focused on optics.
This sensor, although not originally planned by Boyle, now serves as the "eye" of all digital cameras in the world and won him the Nobel Prize in Physics in 2009.
Of course, this does not mean that the activities around the LHC necessarily have to change our lives, but it means that one never really knows...
Palliative care - The best way to get out of life... <0x7C> Le Devoir
Through its Commission for Dignified Dying, Quebec has recently become involved in the delicate issue of the end of life.
