Less than a few weeks ago, Mr. L. was still living alone in his apartment in Monterrey.
Prostate cancer, which was feeding him, gave him a two-year delay.
"They've given me five years to live and it's been seven," he says without emotion on his bed in Victor-Gadbois's palliative care home in Beloeil, where he arrived the day before.
"But it's still a shock, you can't prepare for this," he added.
The disease has done its work: an immense weakness makes it impossible for him to go to the toilet alone or just eat on his own.
He resignedly looks at the tasty-looking breakfast and agrees to help him eat.
He is brave and even smiles, talks to strangers who stop by him, brings him medicines, offers him a bath.
Courage to die a simple death.
"My biggest wish is to get rid of the diarrhea, it humiliates me," she confides.
A few hours later, a team of doctors found a cure for his problem.
"You learn all your life that men pee standing up," says Pierre Brodeur, a psychologist at the Victor-Gadbois facility.
To return to the stage of a child is an unacceptable humiliation for some people.
"It depends on the abilities of the person," the psychologist says, whether he accepts the return.
In the opinion of many palliative care practitioners, crucial moments take place at the very heart of such a return.
Patients entering the home with Victor-Gadbois palliative care all suffer from cancer.
Their prognosis is a maximum of three months of life.
At this stage, the team of doctors and nurses who take care of them does not provide them with so-called "treatment" care.
In the case of Ms. A., 89, the worst fear is to die “of suffocation in full consciousness.”
But the disease allowed me to discover my children.
"I have good children," he added.
"I don't have any wishes in my life anymore," she says, and then she agrees to have her breathing apparatus put on.
However, he is still looking forward to the last visit of his son from Italy in the coming days.
At Victor-Gadbois, in cooperation with a group of volunteers, body care with the help of nutrition is provided.
This is what palliative care looks like when nothing else can be done.
To make death more comfortable.
In Quebec, there is one bed of palliative care per 11,700 inhabitants.
That's very little if we realize that we're all going to die one day.
Here life continues in optimal conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the doctors in the home.
Whether it is a level of physical, emotional or spiritual comfort.
When a person dies, you can give them, for example, a sip of brandy or pepsi, to taste.
Diabetics no longer need to control their sugar levels.
Death is a part of everyday life.
They brought beer to Mr. X last night, who died later that night.
This morning, his son will finish his beer in honor of his deceased father.
“We help patients as well as their loved ones,” says Nathalie Savard, director of care services.
At Victor-Gadbois, the days go by, but they don't resemble each other.
Next to a 93-year-old man who rejoices at his last meeting with his family, thoroughly grounded on pillows, while a toast is given to him in his honor, a 36-year-old man dies tragically surrounded by his parents, wife, and two young children after trying every possible way to survive.
"For six months now, there have always been three to five beds that are designed for people with cancer under 45," says Dr. Christiane Martel.
53% of patients who come to the Victor-Gadbois home come from their homes, 47% from hospitals.
Problems with access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of Canadians simply do not have access to palliative care, that is, care that is designed to alleviate suffering as soon as a sick person reaches the final stage of his or her life, whether at home, in a hospital or in a nursing home.
And several organizations, such as the Victor-Gadbois home and the Society for Home Palliative Treatment of the Grand Montréal area, specialize more or less exclusively in the care provided to cancer patients.
And it is this fundamental unavailability of health care in Quebec that has led many physicians specializing in palliative care to fear the passage of the Euthanasia and Assisted Suicide Act.
Since October, a manifesto has been in circulation signed by leaders in the field of palliative care, such as Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe, in which they demonstrate their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, the Quebec health system is not powerful enough to ensure that all people have access to quality palliative care before they can agree to euthanasia.
She says she recently experienced a patient who spent 14 days in the ER in tremendous pain without anyone taking the necessary steps to relieve her.
He fears that patients will not be asked to be killed because they are not receiving proper care.
And at the same time, many oncologists care for their patients until the last moments, regardless of the unfavorable prognosis.
Chances of survival of Hélène Richard were already quite minimal when she left the demanding chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was quitting treatment, she told us that she regretted that I had stopped fighting.
And yet she told me it was over!
There is no all-powerful care
Dr. Martel estimates that 90% of patients who wish to die thank their attending physicians for not fulfilling their wishes when a team of palliative pussy relieved their pain.
But it must be said that palliative care is definitely not all-powerful in treating pain.
According to Elsie Monereau, director of palliative care at the Society for Home Palliative Care of the Grand Montréal area, patients resist pain treatment in 8% of cases.
At the very end of life, doctors often use palliative sedatives, which put the patient to sleep until the moment of death, either by shock or by being given sedatives permanently.
It is impossible to pretend that we do not perceive this part of suffering.
A patient who is not relieved of pain will have more and more access to palliative sedatives.
Patients who are not given a sedative always say the same thing: “I want to die.”
But that doesn’t necessarily mean “I want you to give me euthanasia,” it means rather “I want you to relieve my pain.”
