Compared to the global exchange for real money or financial products, this is nothing impressive.
And yet, the European Central Bank (ECB) is interested in this fact in its report on virtual finance, which came out in October.
Bitcoin has been described as “the most successful virtual money”, “competing the dollar and the euro” and “the era of ordinary money”.
Bitcoin differs from other types of virtual money in that it is like “credits” used to advance in a video game that a person gains through a game or can buy (and sometimes exchange back).
The social network Facebook has also developed a similar system.
Each month, however, the central authority checks and processes individual communications.
In the case of Bitcoin, all nodes of the network are depository books of current accounts, controllers, money issuers and buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Each transaction between two users actually takes place between two e-mail addresses.
However, the user can choose a different address for each payment, ensuring anonymity.
The file of information related to this transaction is electronically signed by a double-key encryption system.
The network can verify the legitimacy of the transaction.
Thanks to the content of the file, it is also possible to ensure that the exchanged bitcoins exist in the public ledger of current accounts, which is distributed throughout the network.
The key stage lies in the entry of this new transaction into this book.
It is done by solving a mathematical problem assigned to computers, the solver of which, a kind of temporary central banker, will have the right to finish this additional line.
This is the stage of file slicing; i.e. the transformation of a huge file into a shorter and unique digital footprint.
Computers "take over" this new transaction and add a number to it, only then "cut" the whole.
The goal is to find a number that provides a specific footprint (a lot of zeros at the beginning).
Once this number is found, other nodes will easily check its correctness.
The transaction will then be displayed indelibly linked to the string of all other transactions; any modification would change the fingerprint.
If the user wants to pay twice with the same money very quickly in a row (within ten minutes), the network will confirm only one of the two transactions - the other will be abandoned, because each of them has a different footprint.
The computer that solves the challenge wins 50 bitcoins.
In order to avoid inflation, this remuneration is regularly divided by two, probably by the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is limited to 21 million, but they can be divided up to a hundred million, so there is room for margin.
The difficulty of a given task also increases with the increasing level of calculation.
The network has already experienced its ups and downs.
Websites that provide services for Bitcoin have been compromised and stored bitcoins have been stolen.
“The exploited gap is not about the protocol itself,” says Pierre Noizat, who founded Paymium, a real-money payment company that uses the Bitcoin network.
The ECB is also checking the possibility of money laundering through this anonymous service.
But this problem also applies to cash.
Notable players like Wikipedia reject gifts of this nature.
Others, like the WordPress blogging platform, accept them.
Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron of the Weizmann Institute in Israel recently analyzed the current account book and proved that almost 80% of bitcoins do not circulate.
In November, "huge discounts" were launched.
"Thirty thousand dollars have been exchanged," rejoices Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul to convert bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, who is also the author of a pedagogical book on this money, has great confidence in the potential of this technology as a transactional network.
Its system, Paytunia, is equivalent to a credit card (with real money) or contactless mobile payment, but it uses the Bitcoin system to verify transactions that are cheaper as a result.
In addition, the holder manages his identity and can thus remain anonymous.
The system is easy to set up for traders, where there is no need to install new terminals or software.
Just provide an address that can be "photographed and recognized" by the phone, says Pierre Noizat, who assures that it already has thousands of users.
There is a general movement to question hierarchical systems and transition to more horizontal systems.
“It’s going to take a while before Bitcoin takes hold, but 2013 could be a decisive year,” he predicts.
In addition, the ECB’s report foresees a reassessment of various risks that are now considered heightened if this type of money is successful.
