Difficult work on the Egyptian Constitution
President Mohamed Morsi is playing another game of poker.
While Egypt remains the most divided in its history due to the promulgation of a constitution that temporarily grants it unlimited powers, it has decided to play the puppet.
On Wednesday, he announced, irrespective of the views of everyone else, that the Constituent Assembly would approve the final text the following day.
Less than a week ago, the head of state granted the Assembly two more months to complete the necessary work.
Egypt has been using a provisional text for nearly two years, which has been supplemented many times, weakening the country’s constitutional stability and leading to legal controversy.
This new initiative only further strengthened the country's fragmentation.
From the point of view of the opposition, the president remains in his "autocratic delirium", continues to "violate his word" and "trodden the law".
However, his supporters assure him that this is a means of dealing with the constitutional and political crisis as quickly as possible and of speeding up the transition process.
A referendum is to be held in two weeks.
This is a very short period of time, which will force the Brotherhood to withdraw from the intention of the text to the Egyptians to clarify article by article.
It is also a way for the president to regain national and democratic legitimacy while the whole country is rocked by protests.
As he confirmed in an interview with the American weekly Time, Mohamed Morsi seems convinced that Egyptians will vote for him.
Especially since this hastily organized vote puts the Egyptian people before an ultimatum: "Either you approve my text or I will retain unlimited powers", which should otherwise end with the approval of the new constitution.
And in this particular atmosphere, 85 MPs of the aforementioned Constituent Assembly, with a large majority of Islamists, approved the text yesterday.
Most of the Liberals were absent.
In mid-November, not long before the promulgation of the constitution, they slammed the door, saying that they had no opportunity to assert their views.
Human rights defenders, civil society or members of religious minorities have emulated their move.
In order to reach a quorum, 11 alternates were hastily added yesterday morning.
Some of them are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
It is not surprising, then, that the articles of the Constitution were often voted unanimously.
The commentators further paused on the fact that one of the few disputes of the day revolved around... the hour of prayer, when some members of the committee were of the opinion that the hours in the meeting room were not properly set.
The text, which was voted on last night, consists of 234 articles.
The subject of general attention, Article 2, ultimately remains consistent with the 1971 version of the Constitution, stating that "the principles of Sharia law are the main source of law".
Salafist parties, for whom the introduction of Islamic law is one of the fundamental demands, hoped to replace the term "principles" with the term "rules", which would allow for stricter application.
For Islamists, the fact that this article has not been corrected is a sign of their goodwill and respect for other parts of Egyptian society.
"Hypocrisy," the liberals object, who see it as merely a rhetorical problem.
According to them, the Islamization of the Constitution is carried out through other articles.
They focus in particular on Article 220, which entrusts the University of al-Azhar with an advisory role, in particular on issues of checking the conformity of laws with Sharia law.
According to Egypt expert Sophie Pommier, this is disturbing because “persons called to speak are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
This is the beginning of the theocracy.”
Liberal concerns are further fuelled by the fact that the university’s next rector should be less moderate than the current one.
“So far, there has been no concrete religious effect.
With this constitution, Egypt remains a framework civil state.
Most of the lawyers who worked on this text are not Ulams, but university workers, many of them graduated from French schools," Alexis Blouet, who is preparing a paper on constitutional transition in Egypt, said.
However, he agrees that "there may be controversy over the interpretation of Article 220, because the terms used in it belong to the religious vocabulary.
In particular, there is a reference to "fiqh" [Islamic legal science].
And in the future, the question may arise of the extent to which civil judges are competent to make their views known.”
The text approved yesterday, in addition to religious pages, is highly criticized because of the extended powers it confers on the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood insists that they have been severely curtailed compared to the former regime.
Another point of contention: the powers vested in the army.
In accordance with the wishes of the representatives of the military, the verification of the defense budget will not be carried out by the parliament, but by the National Defense Council.
Furthermore, proceedings against civilians will not be prohibited in military courts, as requested by human rights associations.
These associations talk about their doubts in connection with the text, which they say is directed against freedom.
The crime of blasphemy is maintained and insulting continues to be prohibited, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, especially for the press.
No article deals with the protection of women, says Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
According to her, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture laid down in Article 36.
This word was not mentioned in the previous constitution.
While the Egyptian president was scheduled to make a televised speech last night, demonstrations are scheduled for this afternoon.
Proponents of the head of state will then manifest on Saturday.
In Israel, Ukrainian tourists are waiting for holy places, the navel of the world and the sea from a saturated salt solution
The Promised Land combines the greatness of biblical truths, modern comfort and the virginity of nature.
AaF has identified five of the most important reasons why you should visit Israel.
Worship the holy places
Visit the Jordan River, where Jesus was baptized.
It is claimed that God’s mercy will descend on all who enter this “bath.”
And Galilee - the place of the miracles of Jesus: turning water into wine at the wedding, walking on the water, calming the storm and filling the nets.
Here, too, Jesus appeared to his disciples after the resurrection.
Most of the holy places are in Jerusalem.
Believers here will pass the Way of Pain, or the Way of the Cross of Jesus (Latin: Via Dolorosa).
It begins at the fortress of Antonia - Pretoria - where the judgment took place, it passes through the streets of the Old Town and leads to the Temple of the Holy Sepulchre on Mount Golgotha - the place of crucifixion, the anointing stone and the place where Jesus was buried.
Here is the symbolic Christian belly button of the world, which symbolizes the salvation of mankind.
And the monastery of the Holy Cross in Jerusalem was built on the site where, according to Christian legend, a tree grew, from which the cross was made for the crucifixion of Jesus.
Jerusalem is also home to the holiest place for Jews – the Wailing Wall, a remnant of the temple that was destroyed by the Romans in 70 C.E.
According to tradition, people of different faiths here leave notes with wishes, which are then fulfilled.
Embark on a journey through the vertical
The ruins of the fortress of Masada remained from a secret hiding place from the enemy, which Herod the Great built in 25 BC for his family.
The ruins are located on cliffs in the mountains at an altitude of 450 m above sea level.
Only those who are involved in mountaineering can get to it by their own forces.
The rest will be taken to this historic mountain by cable car.
And in the north of the country, at an altitude of 1600-2040 m, there is the famous ski resort Hermon, which experiences a huge influx of tourists in the winter months.
A shuttle bus takes tourists to this ski paradise from the foot of the hill.
The total length of the mountain slopes is 45 km.
According to ancient legend, pagan gods lived on the top of the mountain.
Visit the unique museums
There are about 300 museums in the country.
You can’t visit them all in one trip.
But at least five of them, the most interesting, are definitely worth a visit.
Among them is the Museum of Israel, which is located near the Knesset (Parliament).
It contains ancient Qumran manuscripts, or scrolls from the Dead Sea, found in the caves of the Judean desert, as well as approximately 500,000 archaeological and anthropological exhibits.
Also worth a visit is the Tel Aviv Museum of Art.
His canvases are widely represented by the Impressionists and Expressionists Monet, Pissarro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall, Picasso.
In Akkon, you can visit the Al Basha Spa Museum, which presents visitors with several rooms of ancient Turkish baths with figurines of spa users and spa nurses from that time.
In Caesarea, it is worth visiting the unique private Ralli Museum, where you can admire the statues of Dalí and Rodin.
There are no guides or souvenir shops.
Entrance is free and gifts are strictly refused.
The Fifth Museum – the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem in Tel Aviv – tells the story of one of the most dramatic pages in history.
The most tragic part of the museum - Children's Memorial - was built in memory of the 1.5 million children who were murdered in concentration camps and gas chambers.
You will enter - and you will find yourself in complete darkness.
The stars are glittering.
And the names of the Jewish children and the names of the countries in which they perished.
Ukraine is also mentioned.
Improving your health
Israel's three major spa resorts are located on the Mediterranean, Red and Dead Sea coasts.
Each of them offers swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums and oceanariums.
Interestingly, in the Red Sea it is possible to swim even in the winter months, because the temperature of the water in it does not fall below 21 degrees Celsius, and the air warms up to 23 degrees.
The Dead Sea is even warmer, and people bathe in it all year round.
The Dead Sea, by the way, is the strangest sea in the world, located at the lowest land point of the planet - at the level of 417 m below sea level.
The azure water in it is a saturated salt solution that easily keeps even people who can not swim afloat.
The surrounding countryside is unrealistically beautiful.
Come here to undergo treatment with the use of salt water - brine, and curative mud, which can treat health problems with dermatitis, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes, to cure the damaged nerves.
Touch the mysterious ancient past
It is protected by the ancient part of Tel Aviv - the town of Jaffa on the Mediterranean coast.
The famous sea route connecting Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia passed through them.
References to this city are found in the oldest Greek and Egyptian legends.
According to legend, this is the place where Noah built his ark and Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda, with whom they then lived a long and happy life together.
Tourists really love wandering through narrow streets, named after the signs of the zodiac.
It is said that if you cling to the walls in the alley of "your" sign, luck will favor you.
In Jaffa, you may meet newlyweds who come here from all over Israel and even from other countries to get photographed.
And in Caesarea - in the city of King Herod - you can walk through the Roman theater and "conquer" the fortress of the Crusaders.
In Roman times, Caesarea was the capital of Judea and the seat of Roman prosecutors, including Pontius Pilate.
The carefully reconstructed theatre is now used for evening concerts and opera performances.
Tourists, a word
If you are going to Israel, you do not need to worry about your imperfect English: in this country, about 30% of the population speaks Russian.
For the trip, it is better to take money with you not in euros, but in dollars, which you can easily exchange for shekels (now 1 dollar is about 3.8 shekels).
Buses are the main mode of transport, but there is a high-speed tram in Jerusalem, and the city of Haifa is the only metro line in the country with six stations that connects the lower city with the upper one.
Basically, it's an underground cable car.
Traveling by all types of public transport costs 6 shekels, for which you can drive for 1.5 hours with a change of seats.
In Israel, according to Jewish tradition, the Sabbath is celebrated on Saturday.
From Friday evening to sunset on Saturday, the market, shops and public transport stop working.
On Sunday morning, the working week begins.
In many cafes, restaurants and hotels, you will only get kosher food: with the exception of pork, seafood, fish without scales and dishes that contain combinations of milk and meat.
They offer a large selection of dishes from lamb and beef, soups and desserts, prepared from coconut milk, traditional Jewish hummus porridge, various types of sauces, balls of ground chickpeas - falafel, fruit and vegetables.
There are no stray dogs on the streets of Israeli cities.
But there are a lot of fattened cats that gracefully "wander to their liking".
In the evening you can see them sleeping on the roofs of parked cars.
Precursor cats love crowded places and are eager to engage in every delicacy.
Renting a car will cost between $37 per day (Hyundai Getz) and $188 per day (Audi A6, Volvo S80).
Plus insurance - $15 per day.
And renting a bike will cost about 15 shekels a day.
Tickets to museums cost an average of 30 shekels.
Expressed in numbers
In 2012, more than three million tourists from all over the world visited Israel.
To explore the country and relax came the most citizens of the USA, Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England and Ukraine.
From January to October 2012, 118.8 thousand Ukrainian tourists visited the promised land, which is 51% more than in the same period in 2010, before the abolition of visas on February 9, 2011.
"Great and powerful" announces it to Moscow: emigrants save money on language
While lawmakers and human rights defenders are still debating the law on compulsory language exams, fraudsters have already appeared in the country selling "counterfeit" certificates
Every year, 13 million foreign workers come to Moscow, St. Petersburg and other Russian cities.
Most of them are citizens of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan, Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to earn enough money to support families at home.
On December 1, a law came into force that would require every working migrant to pass a Russian language test.
So far, this rule applies only to those who intend to work in the services, housing and municipality, lifestyle and retail sectors.
However, the FMS promises that in time the relevant tests will be mandatory for all visitors.
However, the exams will consist not only of language skills, but also of Russian history and the basics of law.
Knowledge of the language will also need to be confirmed to obtain and renew a work permit.
The exception applies only to citizens of countries where Russian is the official language.
This law does not apply even to people who successfully achieved attestation and obtained an academic diploma before the collapse of the USSR in 1991.
Benefit, conviction and protection of rights
The network of test sites will work under the auspices of the Pushkin Institute of the Russian Language, the University of Friendship among Nations, Moscow State University, St. Petersburg State University and other Russian universities.
Migrants can take exams in all cities; more than 160 such centers are already open in Russia.
The initiative to support the introduction of testing was also supported by deputies of the State Duma and the FMS (Federal Migration Service).
But before the law came into force, human rights defenders were able to ask in the press many times the question: and what will it actually bring?
What will change the obligation to know the language for Russians and for visitors themselves?
Thus, first of all - according to representatives of the migration service - this will allow to reduce the number of people suffering as a result of "slave labor".
Many people today talk about protecting the rights of migrant workers, explains the Chairman of the Board of Directors of the FMS of Russia in Tajikistan Viktor Sebelev.
The protection of their rights should begin before they leave.
Only a system of organized recruitment will allow 90% to solve the problems of foreign workers.
Problems arise among emigrants without a profession, without education, who do not know the language and do not have a medical examination.
Without knowledge of the language, the future migrant is doomed to clashes with dishonest people who, under the pretext of helping him, will provide a "voucher" to the terrible, cramped hostels in which he and dozens of others like himself will suffer for months without food and documents and work for 12 to 14 hours a day.
We receive many complaints from our migrant workers.
"In their homeland, they promise them one thing, but when they arrive, they cheat them, seize their passports, they do not pay the promised wages," confirms the head of the Main Tajik Department of Labor Migration MS Tolib Sharipov.
Don't bully me!
All the less so because many citizens of the Central Asian republics who intend to go to work in Russia recognize that they not only do not know the language of the country they want to get to, but they do not even have experience with the work in question.
Of course, it’s not so much their fault as their misfortune: very few Turkmens, Uzbeks, Tajiks can afford to get at least an adequate basic education.
After all, their families also need something to feed their children, not to mention the fact that they need to be properly dressed, shod and equipped for school.
As children reach productive age, they must go to work at the first opportunity.
Without knowledge of the language it is difficult - they admit.
"You feel humiliated and inferior."
It is true that, with regard to the Law on Language Examinations, human rights defenders point to one important thing.
Testing will be carried out only on those migrants who have a legal status.
If they don't have it, they won't take the exams, and they won't get any more official jobs.
In the meantime, most migrant workers are living in Russia as illegally as before.
"Welcome, unauthorized entry is not prohibited"
Many of the incoming workers claim that it is not easy to get official status in our country.
The reason - bureaucratic obstacles and all the language difficulties.
Legalization, in addition, costs money: from 12 to 16 thousand rubles.
But fake registration can be obtained quickly and only one and a half thousand.
The Russian police officers know that we have basically fake documents, without registration, and this leads to cases of blackmail.
"They demand a hundred, two for cigarettes, tea," Umed Chuskadamov, a citizen of Tajikistan, told reporters about his experience.
"Come on, don't be greedy, buy a painting"
On the first day of the language law, it was found that not only migrants’ registration documents are false.
FMS employees have already seized several false language exam certificates.
Counterfeit documents are printed on an ordinary colour printer.
Of course, they did not get to the new owners for free: each of the migrants, hoping to facilitate the problem with passing the tests, paid seven thousand rubles for this document.
This is two and a half times higher than passing the official test: it will cost the migrant workers three thousand rubles.
The main task in the near future is to secure the system from corruption so that workers cannot simply buy documents, government officials and human rights defenders agree.
So far, government authorities can promise foreign workers who have failed the tests for the first time the time they need to take a course in the basics of the Russian language.
Visitors who do not speak Russian are expected to work in areas where active interaction with people is not required.
MVD (Ministry of the Interior) does not take into circulation illegal arms market
The proportion of crimes involving the use of legally held weapons is very low
The Ministry of Internal Affairs of Russia is proposing to tighten the law in relation to the owners of civilian weapons.
It is the reaction of the government authorities to recent events: the shootings at weddings, which went without victims, and the massacre prepared by Moscow lawyer Dmitry Vinogradov, which resulted in the deaths of seven people, were the trigger.
Police want to ban the carrying of dangerous weapons in public places and raise the age from which a license to carry weapons can be obtained - from 18 to 21 years.
This idea is supported by the head of the Duma Committee on Security and Combating Corruption, Irina Yarovaya, who promised that changes to the gun law will be submitted to the State Duma in the near future.
Not everyone is satisfied with the fact that the Russian state authorities are trying to deal with the problem by "tightening the screws".
An open letter appeared in the network, the authors of which - representatives of various social shooting organizations - demand a rejection of the "senseless tightening" of the law.
The percentage of hooliganism with registered weapons is minimal, said Vasily Lesnikov, a lawyer and criminalist in an interview with the Russian BBC.
According to the statistics of the Ministry of the Interior, in six months of 2012 142 crimes were committed using firearms registered by the authorities of the Ministry of the Interior, while in the same period a total of 1168 thousand crimes were committed.
The authors of the open letter are convinced that the tightening of legislation in the field of civilian weapons will not induce the perpetrator to move to the "black" market.
According to them, at present, any weapon can be found in Moscow at a low price.
Currently, the Ministry of the Interior says that the situation with the proliferation of illegal weapons is under control.
Suppliers of: from factories to officers
The "black" arms market is supplied by several channels.
There are five main channels, says retired colonel Victor Baranec, who worked for ten years at the Department of Education and the General Staff.
Screenshot of sites that accept orders for weapons
The first of them - "army or military way", that is, a weapon that was stolen during the fighting in the Caucasus.
"Weapons were also stolen by Russian officers and Caucasians themselves," Baranec said.
Another type of "black weapons" are weapons stolen by criminals from representatives of the security forces.
Baranec explains that this includes thefts from police warehouses and weapons stolen directly from employees of law enforcement agencies.
Illegal "mainly" go on sale from military warehouses.
Explosions often occur in many military depots.
"It has been proven that some fires were started deliberately - to cover up the flaw," the former soldier said.
According to Barance, the arms manufacturers are also making their contribution.
“Currently, private arms companies are being created that are not competitive on the international market, and they are eliminating weapons that they supply to the black market, including Moscow,” he said.
Another source of the black market is smuggling.
A particularly large number of pistols and machine guns come from poor countries, such as Kyrgyzstan.
"There is their production, sometimes weapons are made in small-scale production, and a mafia was formed that organized their smooth production," the former soldier explains.
Where'd the gun come from?
Experts have summarized the approximate share of the various sources of supply of illegal weapons to the “black” market.
A report on this issue was prepared in 2011 by the Center for Problem Analysis and Public Administration Design.
Specialists analyzed reports from the Ministry of the Interior and the Russian Statistical Office, criminological literature and data from public data portals focused on the topic of weapons.
The vast majority of illegal weapons, researchers say, come from military and executive bodies.
Half of all weapons found themselves on the black market “by officials whose work is linked to weapons,” the report said.
According to the data available to the researchers, 17% of weapons come from armed conflicts, in 14% of cases there was theft of weapons during their manufacture, 5% is "black archaeology".
A salesman-consultant of one of the arms stores, who asked us not to mention his name, is convinced that the weapons found in the excavations by black "archaeologists" have long since been bought by anyone - they are simply too old.
Most often, as he says, sellers go for new shipments directly to military warehouses.
