Perhaps the system will be so overwhelmed with paper that those who want to look for holes in the system will draw on it much more easily than if the limit remained higher.
You are talking about domestic problems with the transposition of public procurement legislation into practice.
How does the control system work in Germany?
Is there an office similar to our SAO, or is it set differently?
As far as the offices are concerned, just as the SAO operates there, the Bundesrechnungshof, which is organized similarly to us, also has a college, it is only formed in a slightly different way, but in principle both offices proceed in a similar way.
The powers are also similar to some extent, but because Germany has a federal system, it also has these courts of account at the level of individual federal states - in this the system differs a little from ours.
BRH can only control federal money, represented by state funds.
The public funds administered by the counties and municipalities in our country are checked there from the level of the federal accounting courts.
As far as the legislation is concerned, is it easier than ours?
In general, I would not like to compare it without specific data, but in some respects Germany is referred to as a model, but it is not certain that it is better in everything.
Is it because they have better controls?
Certainly not, but again, I don't like comparisons.
But it must be said that even countries that we consider to be role models face a number of problems.
Otherwise, it would be of no benefit to them to cooperate with our office, would it not?
As for the domestic legislation, what did the amendment of the law on public procurement mean for your office, are its effects already manifested in some way?
Due to the fact that the period of validity of this amendment is relatively short, it does not yet manifest itself in our control actions.
Since we do ex-post checks, there is a certain delay to be reckoned with.
We are only observing this in the process of preparing future checks - we have launched our new tool for "detection of risks of inefficiencies", through which we have run almost 14,000 public contracts, and we have analyzed them - there, of course, these changes will manifest themselves, because the limits will change, the conditions of some types of tenders will be adjusted, and so on.
So do you see the adoption of this law as more of a benefit or a further burden on the bureaucracy system?
I think that this law is certainly a step in the right direction, and I hope that it will be confirmed.
The problem that may arise here is that the rules will be "tightened" and it will not be possible to comply with them.
Already for the operation of the previous rules, the audited persons are obliged by the provider (for example, in the case of regional operational programmes by the regional council) to the fact that any non-compliance with the law on public procurement constitutes a violation of budgetary discipline.
Is it worth it to tighten the law in this way?
I don't think so.
The system must exclude those who want to attack and abuse it, and not punish those who commit a formal misconduct that has no impact on decision-making.
Such a system will only put more pressure on the bureaucracy.
So how do we get out of this?
Let's see where the road leads.
Recently, the Prime Minister said that the ODS would not bother entrepreneurs with controlling the so-called "swarz system" - and what does that mean?
Is the black system banned or allowed?
After all, the law has to be set somehow, and if it prohibits something, then even the Prime Minister cannot prevent the work of the office, which has the duty to monitor and enforce duties.
He can say, "We're going to change the law and allow it," but he can't say that we're going to act like nothing.
There are fairly strict rules in the Public Procurement Act on how to formally do what is right to protect competition.
But on the other hand, it is tragic when the candidate with the best offer is excluded only for formal shortcomings.
The law will never be perfect, but its application must be correct - that is what is lacking in our opinion.
