Poland and space.
Last week, at a meeting of the ministers of the countries of the European Space Agency, Poland was accepted as the 20th member of the European Space Agency, as the second country from the countries of the former Eastern Bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became a full member of ESA on November 12, 2008).
Poland started working closely with ESA in 1994 and has been involved in a number of ESA projects over the years.
However, Poland’s journey into space began much earlier.
Polish spaceflight enthusiasts had been engaged in before World War II; but they did not always meet with understanding.
I will recall, for example, A. Sternfeld’s lecture at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory, which on 6 December 1933 presented the ideas from his pioneering work The Entry into Cosmonautics.
The ideas of the young engineer (born 1905) left the audience cold, and after years Sternfeld recalled that only Dr. Jan Gadomski was interested in his work.
In 1934, Sternfeld was awarded the Robert Esnault-Pelteri and André Louis Hirsch Prize for his Entry into Space in France.
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899-1966) became a great promoter of astronomy and cosmonautics.
He has published hundreds of articles in Polish journals and has written a number of books devoted to these scientific disciplines.
Gadomski became a world-renowned promoter of cosmonautics, and his contribution was also appreciated by the fact that one of the craters on the far side of the moon was named after him.
Already in 1925, a railway train was built in Poland, which was to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, the author of the design is not known and the details of the project are not known.
It is unclear whether the missile was to be used to start the train or to brake it.
Information about this dresin is known only from the contemporary press.
In 1933, Polish artillery began to use rockets.
The research was carried out by the Arms Technology Cell in cooperation with Prof. Mieczyslaw Wolfk and Prof. Gustav Mokrzyckiegi.
From the preserved materials it is clear that the research has reached the stage of practical tests.
However, with the arrival of German troops, the research was interrupted.
In 1937, the design of a photoelectric fighter missile, designed by engineer Rohozinski, appeared in the professional press, and the following year the work Rocket - torpedo wyrzeda i rakietobomba lotnicza by Leliwy-Krzywoblockego was published.
Both projects were intended for the military use of rocket engines.
Just before the war, the Provisional Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy) devoted all the projects of military use of missile technology, which coordinated all the work.
The committee was established in 1937, but after two years of activity, its activities ended the start of the war.
After the war, other works devoted to cosmonautics appeared in the Polish press thanks to the work of the Polish Astronautical Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
For the first time, the company is mentioned in the November 1954 issue of the journal Problemy, which contains four more extensive articles on astronautics.
In one of them, from Prof. M. Subotowicz, it is proposed to create a company that will deal with cosmonautics.
At that time, artificial satellite projects were already underway, and it was clear that space research was a promising field.
Since the beginning of 1956, the Polish Astronautical Society (PTA) has been trying to join the International Astronautical Federation (founded in 1951), and already in the fall, PTA became a full member.
And in the following year, the first chairman of the PTA Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959) became vice-chairman of the International Astronautical Federation.
He held this position until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, the PTA has been instrumental in the development of the highly successful RM (Meteorological Rocket), which became the first Polish rocket to carry out scientific research.
The first type RM-1 was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
The rocket with a range of 1800 meters was about 80 cm long and its weight was less than 5 kg.
Later, an improved version of the RM-1A was built, and in the summer of 1959, flight tests of the two-stage RM-2 rocket began in the Bled Desert.
The rocket was 1.4 meters long and weighed about 11.5 kg.
The next development type was to be able to do real scientific work - the RM-34 rocket was to have an access of up to 14.5 km and its task was to monitor the high-altitude wind.
However, in 1962, further development was suspended.
The first RM rocket was the Meteor-1, which was developed between 1962 and 1965.
The rocket was designed as a two-stage, its total length was 510 cm and the starting weight was 32.5 kg.
Three types (designated Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed, which differed in space size for scientific instruments.
In the rocket Meteor-1A was available space with a volume of 0.4 liters, Meteor-1B with a volume of 0.34 liters and Meteor-1C with a volume of 0.62 liters.
The maximum access for all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Meteor-2 rocket was developed at the Aviation Institute, and its first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had a launch weight of 380 kg and was able to carry a payload of 10 kg to a height of about 60 km.
Subsequently, the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were built.
Poland joined the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and created the COSPAR National Committee two years later.
Poland was also involved in space exploration on Soviet artificial satellites as part of the Interkosmos program, and in 1978 Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimir Remko.
Abolishing the Public Works Act is not the solution.
Last week, the Constitutional Court overturned the Public Works Act.
The resolution sparked a lively public debate.
It will certainly be interesting to look at the issue from a broader perspective.
Liberally oriented economic systems in the EU as well as in a globalized world are based on the principle of more, unregulated competition.
In effect, this means that individual economic entities, national economic systems, are in permanent conflict with each other.
The reason is the principle of free trade and the free, unrestricted movement of private capital, together with unbridled financial speculation.
Due to the significant differences in the price of labor, (wages) there are price tensions.
Under this term, it is necessary to understand the situation in which a producer tries to compete by importing cheap goods by "beating" the price of a competitor in order to attract more market share and thereby increase its own profits.
On a mass scale, this means for most entrepreneurs to either transfer production abroad, or buy cheaply there, or disappear.The result is high unemployment in countries where labor prices are high compared to other economies.
Since private capital has no social responsibility and hence no responsibility for the unemployment it produces, the social expenditure of the state necessarily increases.
The whole situation is aggravated by the complete reluctance of entrepreneurs to pay taxes and thus to compensate for the economic and social harm that he caused in the pursuit of profit.
The situation is so well known that it is not necessary to provide specific statistical data.
The reckless practices of private capital create a situation in individual economies in which the governments of individual countries are forced to enter into competition with each other in order to artificially reduce the social level of their own population in order to attract foreign capital to the country.
In other words, governments give private capital a chance on its own population, regardless of social decline.
This is mainly reflected in the changes to the current laws.
The aim is to economically force its own population to accept the price dictate of private capital, especially in the area of wages.
This is done, on the one hand, by the system of economic coercion in the case of long-term unemployment, and, on the other hand, by the restriction of workers' rights in the field of labour law.
The result is increasing poverty, along with growing disparities between the poor and the rich.
For many years, there have been public food dispensaries in Germany for the poor, who cannot make a living by their own work.
The number of these people is already in the millions.
As part of increasing the competitiveness of the German economy, it is quite common for people who are properly employed to receive such a salary that the state has to pay them up to the subsistence minimum.
Such a scandal was also made public in the case of auxiliary employees of the Bundestag.
The austerity measures of virtually all southern EU states undoubtedly lead to the same situation where people, under the pressure of a catastrophic decline in the social level, are forced to either emigrate as they did in the 19th century, or to live on starving wages on the margins of society in the hope that private investment capital may one day come to the country.
The question is, where does it come from?
If it is from other EU countries, then poverty will move from one country to another, or it will not come at all, because a Chinese, an Indian, a Brazilian, a Turk, a Moroccan, an Egyptian, or an African still work for a fraction of the European wage.
This applies to the whole of Latin America.
Liberal theory and the media argue that the state cannot participate capitally in its own economy, that a controlled economy leads to economic catastrophe.
The private capital firmly insists that the State must not intervene in the economy through managerial interventions.
Then it is necessary to ask whether private capital does not influence, now actually controls politics, and thus the whole state in its own egoistic sense.
Here is a clear answer yes.
The proof is the existence of an almost omnipotent and ubiquitous lobby in all states.
The result is a desperate situation manifested in the field of corruption, the provision of mutual benefits, legislation, where practically everything is criminal, but nothing is criminal.
In Germany, the situation is such that state ministries, for lack of funds, commission private law firms, which are often associated with industry, to draft laws.
These bills are then approved by the Bundestag.
All power thus comes not from the people as proclaimed by Western-type constitutions, but from financially strong groups preferring their own interests.
It is evident that liberal-oriented democracies are now rapidly getting into a situation, as Appianus describes it in his Crisis of the Roman Republic in the days of Caesar and Pompey: "The state has long been in complete disintegration and the offices have been occupied by violence.
For bribes, illegal gaining of favor, and with the help of stones or swords.
Bribery and corruption prospered without any hindrance, and the people went to the elections with a pre-sold vote" ..."characteristic people did not apply for office at all, so once as a result of this disruption was the state eight months without consuls." .."Indeed, it began to be said that the only remedy in a bad situation is self-government."
Conclusion As in antiquity, modern society is based on the reckless preference of self-interest, regardless of the overall social interest.
By its very nature, private capital is no longer able to understand and apply the general benefit of society.
The result is now, as then, an unprecedented decadence of the elites without any deeper reform efforts.
The causality of the rise of fascist and communist regimes must therefore be sought in the reckless liberalization of the economic systems of the 19th and 20th centuries.
In the current state of affairs, the demise of these systems in favour of a liberal-type democracy can be considered a break with the expectation of the next round.
Particularly disastrous is the fact that the current elites completely ignore in the future the possible loss of hundreds of thousands of lives, humanitarian and social disasters, which we are already witnessing together with crimes against humanity, as we know from old and new history.
The repeal of the Public Works Act is not a solution, at least not permanent.
Under the pressure of competition both at the international and intra-European level, the government of the Czech Republic will be forced to continue to look for ways to further reduce the social level of the population.
This trend is systemic.
The solution is targeted political and social reforms that will strengthen the state’s capital participation in the economy, strengthen the influence of citizens on the government, and weaken the monopoly position of private capital in society for the benefit of the state.
