Argo: When It's Worst, Call Hollywood
In November 1979, a mob of Islamist students seized the U.S. embassy in Tehran and took 52 diplomats hostage.
They were to be released in exchange for the ousted Shah Mohammed Reza Páhlavi, who fled to the United States after the revolution, which had been the patron of his regime for decades.
For the US administration, the situation did not offer a positive outlet - she could not afford to throw the shah overboard, because it would fundamentally jeopardize the confidence of allies in other countries.
However, the release of the hostages in Iran, where the revolution resulted in the establishment of a theocratic regime, was not possible.
It was a blow to the prestige of the United States, which was later deepened by the fiasco of the attempt to free the hostages by force.
The detainees were finally released after 444 days, after the Algerian government brokered the negotiations.
Their fate at home has sparked a wave of solidarity and anti-Iran sentiment.
The debacle in Iran contributed significantly to Jimmy Carter's loss to Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
The film directed by Ben Affleck Argo describes one episode of the story that brought America a small victory.
Just before the embassy was occupied, six employees fled.
After difficult peripeties, they ended up in the residence of the Canadian ambassador.
The CIA, in cooperation with the Canadian authorities, managed to get them out of Iran, helped by an extravagant cover story - they went to Canadian passports as members of the film crew who were inspecting the country's locations for shooting a sci-fi big movie.
Combination of genres
The plan, devised by "exfiltration" expert Tony Mendez, also required Hollywood's co-operation.
For the legend to be credible, a film project was written in specialized magazines, press conferences were held, a fictional production company had a real office.
Details of the operation were kept secret for a long time, the film is based on the memories of Tony Mendez.
Affleck's film is a special combination of multiple genres.
On the one hand, a realistic political thriller, at the same time the so-called "caper movie", the story of a successful piece of trickery - an example can be the series of Danny's partners.
In the film, moods alternate - on the one hand, documentary sequences from Tehran (the subtitle sequence shows iconic period photographs of events and the way in which the same situations were presented in the film - there are no big differences in this).
On the other hand, lighter passages from Hollywood, negotiated with irony and a slight exaggeration.
And then there are scenes from the CIA headquarters and other institutions - men in suits discussing the situation at the negotiating tables, in the corridors of the office, on the phone...
Ben Affleck had a remarkable career restart.
From a ridiculed actor, he became a respected director, and even his acting ceased to be the target of ironic remarks.
Argo is his third feature film, after the dark crime series Gone Baby Gone (2007) and the thriller City (2010).
It is also Affleck's first film not set in the director's hometown of Boston.
At the same time, the feeling for the atmosphere of the place was among the characteristics that raised the director’s older films above the Hollywood standard.
And Affleck also shows it in Argo, where Tehran "plays" Canada.
The best scenes in the film take place in the streets, in the reconstruction of real events - the opening sequence of the fall of the embassy is impressive in its clarity, which at the same time conveys the emotions of confusion and unpredictability that occur when history suddenly moves somewhere.
Affleck and his associates achieve a similar effect in fictional scenes (the fake headquarters at the Tehran bazaar).
Too much action in too many places
The director also had to deal with the fact that the story told does not actually offer much in the film sense of thrilling scenes.
He works with it quite successfully, sometimes he comes up with something to reality - everything does not work out so elegantly there (the scene in which the impending crisis at the Tehran airport turns away the phone call in America and the chase after the runway seems quite drawn to his hair).
The weakness of Argo, however, is the distraction resulting from the need to show too many events in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman are very charming in their roles as Hollywood co-workers, but their characters would deserve more space and they are not the only ones in the film.
Affleck’s film is losing a bit of dramatic momentum, it is a film that can be watched with a slight interest, appreciate the realization and retro style evoking the thrillers of the 1970s.
