The architects of the MVRDV are proof that real adventures do not take place only in the head - for example, Spijkenisse and the recently built Mountain of Books - 2 images
"The building looks cheerful, it looks futuristic, finally there's something interesting to see again," says Lisette Verhaig, who walks by the side of the road.
Stefan Spermon, an IT technician at a nearby large enterprise, says: "Of course, the house is nice."
But I wonder why we still need a library today.
They all have internet, iPads and e-books.
Nobody volunteers to go to any of these old-fashioned libraries anymore, right?
Spijkenisse, a housing estate in the immediate vicinity of Rotterdam with no job opportunities of its own, which is not even worth a visit, holds a special record.
With a population of 80,000, this municipality has the lowest education rate in the whole of the Netherlands.
To resolve this stupid situation, the decision was made a few years ago to contribute to general education and build seven nicely painted reinforced concrete miniatures of fictitious bridges, which are depicted on euro banknotes.
But the success of the educational offensive was not at all daunting.
And so the city councillors realized that there is only one way to become masters of statistics: we must have a library!
Winy Maas of the Rotterdam architectural studio MVRDV, master of insanely bold column graphs and maker of funny, often even cynical buildings, accepted the matter with the usual calm and appeared at the competition in 2003 with five books under his arm and a smile on his face.
And while the commission was still looking around in amazement and shrugging its shoulders, the impudent Maas placed his gifts on himself according to the size and ended his activist-reasoned speech with the words, "Dear urban community!"
So this is my proposal for the Book Mountain in Spijkenisse, the so-called Boekenberg!
Nine years later, the mountain was built for 30 million euros.
It is part of a revitalization project, which also includes an underground parking lot, a supermarket, a post office and several adjacent residential and terraced houses with a total of 50 apartments.
In early November, the Book Mountain was awarded the second place "Best Library of NL 2012".
The project is nominated for the 2012 Dutch National Wood Award.
Small town grey, which so far could not offer more than a postmodern pedestrian zone and an unusually ugly town hall, behind the white facade of which you would rather expect a dairy, is richer in a bit of contemporary architecture.
Above all, Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in the history of its existence.
The Long Road to the Book
First impression: reader's eldorado under the cheese hatch.
Although the elevator runs through the mountain massif, you will discover the real spatial and reading passions only when you climb the topography on foot.
On all sides, the glazed interior is bright and clear, the floor of a burnt cabbage and elegant street lanterns clearly express the atmosphere of a public square.
The urban environment is perfect.
You see park benches, a dog and boys and girls playing football.
And everywhere books, books, books.
“Normally, bookshelves stand along the facade and in the middle is a large dark space that is mostly uncomfortable and impersonal,” says Winy Maas.
We built the classic spatial configuration upside down and pushed the space for the readers from the inside out.
The inside of the Book Mountain is cleverly used: in the middle there are offices, an Internet library, a chess club, an ecological center and a home appliances center.
A special delight is the black bookshelves, which are one wall cladding, one window sill, and sometimes a stair railing.
The appearance, structure and smell are foreign.
Even sworn architects and civil engineers shake their heads over the unknown building material.
“We wanted to work here with recycled materials,” says Joop Trouborst, project manager at Spijkenisse, in a request to Standard magazine.
So one day, at a Frisian farm, we came across a suitable agricultural waste product.
For many years, millimeter fleece made of synthetic material has been used as a substrate under the roots in greenhouses and fields in the Netherlands.
It is cheap and time-efficient.
Thin textiles last for one, two seasons, and then are ripe for disposal in bulky waste.
For the library, the fleece - for the first time in such a quantity - was pressed on boards four centimeters thick.
Under the influence of heat and pressure, the so-called Landbouwplastic (KLP) turns into a dark, homogeneous and load-bearing material that smells a bit like a new car and a bit like sports shoes.
Take the 105 steps to the top.
At the end of the almost 500 m long walk, you will be rewarded in the literary café not only with fantastic views of the city, but also with Dutch croquettes and figs in pots.
They care about the atmosphere, but mainly about the right humidity in the mountains of literature.
Gifts for a New Soul
"You probably wouldn't believe it, but this house, despite the many glass surfaces, is an exemplary project when it comes to ecology," Trouborst says.
It is heated and cooled by the earth's heat.
Although the Mountain of Books stands under a glass hatch, the sun shines only briefly inside, even on sunny days.
Wide glued wooden ties, which stand perpendicular to the glazed facade, serve as a shading and capture a large part of the sun's rays.
The climate in the room is very pleasant.
The rest can handle fully automatic roller shutters.
Stefan Spermon, an early IT skeptic, has already visited the new library.
Lisette Verhaig was already there.
And also the teacher of traditional Chinese medicine Cynthia Bogarde, who even calls Boekenberg the "long-awaited soul" of Spijkenisse.
The reason: every resident of the city was invited to the opening a few weeks ago to donate one book from his personal fund.
First, the optical gaps in the not yet fully equipped library, which currently has 70,000 copies, were to be filled.
The concept has proven itself.
The shelves are completely filled.
"There is nothing worse than a half-empty library," says architect Winy Maas.
"I think that thanks to our invitation, every resident now has a certain relationship with the new house.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
Even if it's just for decoration.
Thus, the MVRDV succeeded in the royal discipline, which in professional jargon is called identity formation.
Spijkenisse wrote the history of literature.
No matter how young and uneducated they are.
This is the starting point for identity.
