"In fact, boredom has a long history," he said.
On the walls of Pompeii was found a Latin inscription concerning boredom, dating from the first century AD.
And then there's the question of how we define boredom.
The difficulty is that it has been defined and discussed in many different ways, said John D. Eastwood, a professor of psychology at York University in Ontario, Canada.
After reviewing the research literature and presenting the idea to a target group of about 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues defined boredom as the experience of "I wanted to do something that would satisfy me, but I wasn't able to."
Boredom differs from apathy in that a person is not involved in anything, but would like to be.
He says that in apathy there is no compulsion to do something.
He says that the core of boredom is "disturbing the process of attention, associated with a bad mood and a sense of slow-moving time."
Boredom can resemble depression.
But Professor Eastwood said that while they can have a relationship with each other, bored people tend to see the problem as the environment or the world, while people who are depressed see the problem in themselves.
