On the other hand, many philosophers and writers have debated the link between boredom and creativity, said Professor Vodanovich, who has studied the problem for more than two decades.
“Boredom is the brain’s way of telling you that you should be doing something else,” said Gary Marcus, a professor of psychology at NYU.
But the brain doesn’t always know the best thing to do.
If you are bored and use this energy to play guitar and cook, it will make you happy.
However, if you watch TV, it will only make you happy for a while, not for a long time.
So if your child is bored and you give him an iPad, he will no longer be bored, but he will not learn how to entertain himself or drive independently, Professor Fenske said.
And "this separate management is transferred from one situation to another," the professor said.
Your child will not only learn how to have fun on their own, but will gain more self-control in other areas.
I don't think we really want to celebrate boredom.
