What is private offline is private and online
-Privacy.
According to the dictionary published by the Royal Spanish Academy, this is something of a personal nature or an “area of private life that everyone has the right to protect against any interference”.
What is privacy for a person under the age of 16?
How does he apply this definition in his daily life and on social networks?
Does he understand the dangers to which he is exposed when he publishes things on the Internet that he would certainly not tell anyone during normal communication?
Journalists from elPeriódico interviewed five boys and girls between the ages of 10 and 15 who are frequent users of the Internet.
In four cases, they considered the concept of privacy to be "something entirely of their own" on a personal level and a "username and password" if it was a social network.
“I wouldn’t reveal my biggest secrets,” Jorge, 10, said in an effort to explain the importance of privacy in places like Facebook, Twitter, Hotmail and Windows Live Messenger, where he has had accounts for two years.
"They're very secret secrets, my mom may know about them, but not the whole world," she says.
"I'm posting nice photos or photos of us playing on FB.
I also talk to friends there.
“I wouldn’t share a photo that wasn’t mine, or a photo that made someone laugh,” she said.
This boy realizes that it is wrong to publish obscene photos, photos of naked persons or photos of crimes, or to write degrading or rude comments.
Jorge says he knows all 35 friends he has on FB and his nine Twitter followers.
Most of them are relatives.
Among them is a mother who has the name and password of one of the accounts.
“I set up a Twitter account to express my views and write interesting posts.
I don’t know if anyone will answer me, I just put them there,” he adds.
“Social networks are fun, I can talk to relatives who are far away or quickly communicate with friends,” she says.
Without hesitation, he says he would never accept a request from an unknown person.
He wouldn't even care if someone recommended him to someone he didn't know.
The case of fourteen-year-old Jose is different.
He owns accounts on Hotmail, Facebook, My Space and Ask, and admits he doesn’t know 20 people on his friends list.
"I'm not afraid of that because we have something in common, like music," he says.
According to this boy, none of them were inducing him to do anything, or asking him for an address or a phone number.
"If they urged me or asked me to do so, I would simply remove them from my account," he admits.
José signed up for Ask after reading the recommendation on Twitter.
These guys are no strangers to what is now called cyberbullying.
"A friend of mine was blackmailed on a social network.
They threatened him and asked for money.
He never knew who he was," he said.
According to Jose, the victim didn't log out of the account.
"You just activated the private mode."
Then it explains a series of steps on how to set up an account securely.
Unlike Jorge, this boy would post photos of famous people in uncomfortable or embarrassing situations.
"Of course I would if someone bothered me or if I just wanted to.
“I know it’s cyberbullying,” he said.
Key Questions
Marielos Porras, an English teacher and a graduate in Education and Teaching, believes that in order for children and adolescents to navigate social networks correctly, they must understand that the main goal of these networks is to inform.
“The Internet was created as a means of finding information, but when social networks appeared, the rules of the game changed.”
Marrielos Porras notes that academic Marc Prensky, a graduate of pedagogy at Yale University and author of the paper Digital Natives and Digital Immigrants, introduced these concepts to explain the phenomenon.
“Digital natives are children and young people who were born in the age of technology.
We are digital immigrants who have to teach them, and yet we are just learning ourselves," he says.
It is a complex subject, he explains, “because we ask them to discern what is appropriate to disseminate, publish and say, and what is not, at an age when they are not yet ripe for it.”
Also, to be – as far as the environment is concerned – prudent, at a time when what they want most is to be popular, to have thousands of friends and not to think about the consequences.”
According to this specialist, the most effective way to show children and adolescents what privacy is is to ask questions that make them think.
“Telling them not to do something doesn’t work,” he added.
Next, Marrielos Porras lists some of the possibilities: There are things you wouldn’t tell a stranger, so why do you do it on the Internet?
Or: Would you like someone to post a picture of you the way you posted a friend?
Do you know what others are posting about you?
When you mark people in the photos of the celebrations, did you ask them for permission?
And one more thing: Does everyone always need to know what you’re doing right now?
The next point is to make them realize that they must behave in the Internet environment as well as outside it.
It's the same rules.
“Outside the internet, one is guided by respect, morals and other principles, and the same should be true on social media,” he said.
Supervision
Estuardo Guardia, a university professor, first-year teacher and educational advisor explains that it is necessary for parents of children to carefully read the rules of social networks.
“If they understand every trick, they have a good basis to talk to their children about the consequences of opening an online account.
For example, in terms of age or what is allowed to be shared or published,” he says.
The Guardian believes that it is crucial to remind children of the traditional rule of “don’t talk to strangers”.
