AIDS victims today are the result of late diagnosis
Fabrizio was 21 years old when his test result was confirmed: HIV-positive.
"It was as if a lightning bolt had struck me," he recounts, recalling a moment of truth that the doctor had tried to "moderate a little," but apparently without success.
The boy kept it from his family.
He decided to take his illness on his own shoulders and began to inform himself about it, with such a commitment that he had already celebrated his 43rd birthday.
He is undoubtedly one of the oldest patients of the HIV Unit at the Guadalajara Civil Hospital (HCG), to which he came in 1994 after several battles with the disease.
Fabrizio has been living with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) since the age of 22, something unimaginable in the early 1990s, when there was a lot of doubt, few treatment options, and greater stigma.
At the time, the director of the Mexican Institute of Social Security (IMSS) did not say goodbye to him, “because he had a cut.”
AIDS was synonymous with death.
Now it is possible to survive with this syndrome and live fully.
However, there are many people who do not know about their disease and come only when the virus has destroyed the body and weakened the immune system, and then become victims of accidental infections.
31 years after the emergence of AIDS in the world, or at least since the first documented cases, "means great success that the life expectancy of a patient who starts treatment in a timely and appropriate manner is exactly the same as in healthy people," said Jaime Andrade Villanueva, head of the HIV Unit at the Civil Hospital in Guadalajara.
HIV/AIDS specialist Andrade Villanueva explained that scientists have concluded that since 2008 AIDS is not a death sentence, but that the duration of survival and a full life depends on the degree of impairment of the immune system of patients diagnosed with the disease, while those who do not use drugs are better off: people with CD4 cells can live for up to 200 years.
Simply put, this means that a person who is diagnosed with HIV at 25 years of age can live without problems up to 75 years, according to these findings, while adhering to treatment, the doctor explained in an interview.
To highlight this progress, it is worth recalling that the average life expectancy of Mexicans today is 76 years.
Although the mortality rate has declined significantly in recent years, and in the case of Mexico, the number of people who died from AIDS fell from 6,678 in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (United Nations Joint Programme on HIV/AIDS - UNAIDS Yearbook), it is also true that 60 percent of patients have died since the discovery of AIDS, according to national statistics.
In the state of Jalisco alone, 255 people died in 2011 and 187 so far this May. However, universal access to antiretrovirals has been ensured since 2005.
Why do people continue to die from the disease?
"It seems to me that the problem is not in the options of access to treatment.
That's how I see it, that's how it happens in our hospital.
At least in the last 12 years, we have not exhausted our supply of medicines, but the problem is that patients arrive at a very advanced stage because they do not know the state of the disease, that is, at a late stage of the disease."
He adds a compelling figure: "Nine out of ten patients come when an associated infection is already manifested. All that needs to be done in order to have a greater impact on overall mortality is to diagnose the disease earlier, so it is necessary to offer large-scale tests to detect the disease to all people who ask for it."
In his proposal, he agrees with specialists and officials from the State Council for the Prevention of AIDS in the state of Jalisco, as well as directly with patients like Fabrizio, who came to have tests done in a private laboratory just because his friend did it, and despite his small age, he already had an AIDS outbreak and also suffered from Kaposi's sarcoma, a cancer that is one of the diseases.
"Everything changes when you know you have AIDS.
Some think they're going to die, and they don't want to know anything else.
"If I'm going to die, I'd rather get three times a week," they say, but that's not my case.
The change was for the better, I eat healthy, I exercise, I take medication.”
To this day, all his parents know is that he suffered from cancer.
“I live a normal life like everyone else.
I work, I have a lot of activities, I travel, I lead an active sex life, but responsibly, I take care of myself and the other person," says Fabrizio, who accepted the invitation to share his experience with the daily MILENIO JALISCO, to motivate those who are afraid with his testimony today as part of World AIDS Day.
"Let them get tested. If they risked it, let them know as soon as possible if they're HIV-positive, it's better. And if they've already been diagnosed, let them realize that they can live like anyone else if they're responsible."
This message summarizes the theme of this year’s battle against AIDS.
Condoms behind the counter
There is a big gap between health programs and ordinary citizens, said Ricardo Salazar, a Guadalajara-based journalist who seeks information about HIV.
And the biggest gaps are in prevention.
In places dedicated to this task, "the distribution of condoms has really increased, once they gave us one or two, now they give us packs and a hundred condoms, which is very good, but there are still people who do not have access to condoms," he said.
Adolescents are among the most susceptible to new infections.
“What do you want it for?” is a common question full of irony and judgment from social workers, school counselors, pharmacy workers, and medical staff that teens want to avoid, the reporter says.
He suggested changing this ineffective distribution, so that condoms were not just behind the counters, but in the hundreds of dispensers in public toilets, in places where young people often go.
“It’s not about promiscuity.
It’s not even about “paying for beer and a motel,” as Governor Emilio González said when asked if he would agree to distribute condoms in his district.
It’s best to make condoms available to those who already have sex,” he said.
Key figures in the state of Jalisco
There were 13,435 cases (12,158 cases of AIDS and 1,317 cases of HIV).
In Mexico, the condition ranks fourth in new and detected cases of AIDS and 13th in HIV-related cases.
92% of infections occur sexually, 6% by blood and 2% perinatally.
It is estimated that about 50,000 people can live with HIV, as there are four to five people who are unaware of the disease per registered case.
The judgment approved by the United States Court of Appeal, which does not recognize the restructuring of Grupo Vitro’s debt as stipulated by the bankruptcy in Mexico, sets an unfortunate precedent for any national enterprise with branches in a neighboring country and solvency issues.
Thus, it seems that the corporate restructuring procedures that are allowed by Mexican law do not apply in the country of stripes and stars despite international agreements.
The approval of Judge Harlin Hale’s ruling on June 15 last year in the Northern Texas Insolvency Court leaves Mexican firms unprotected in practice against the possibility of confiscating their assets on the other side of the Bravo River.
However, the verdict opens the door for a major Mexican glass manufacturer to the United States Supreme Court with an appeal against three irregularities.
To begin with, while the judge of this case claims that creditors are to be governed by the United States insolvency law, the Fifth Circuit Court of Appeals, based in New Orleans, says that the main procedure sets out bankruptcy proceedings in Mexico.
Firstly, it would indicate ignorance of international procedural cooperation in cases of insolvency of multinational enterprises.
Basically, for this purpose, the United Nations Model Law for the Unification of International Commercial Law was created, which determines the American Law Institute as an arbitrator.
Secondly, the judgment provides that without a vote by the branches of the internal corporate structure, when the debt of the parent company Vitro to the branches is recognised, the required majority for the approval of the restructuring would not have been achieved.
However, Mexican law allows for this possibility.
The fact is that the Vitro case was not the first in which this scheme was adopted.
There are half a dozen examples, such as Agremex and Comercial Mexicana, whose corporate debts were guaranteed by the Federal Bankruptcy Institute.
In addition, it is true that even after deducting the votes of the branches, the creditors - who opposed Vitro in court in the United States, i.e. "soup" funds such as Aurelios Capital, Aurelios Convergencia, Elliot International and Liverpool Limited - would not have obtained a majority.
In the vote, they would reach about 45 percent to 37 percent.
This figure is not taken into account by the Court of Appeal.
From another point of view, the court blames Vitro for the difficult situation it has faced since 2008 - against the backdrop of a serious economic crisis that has hit the United States.
In the meantime, Gonzalez Sady’s family firm will appeal to the Court of Appeals for a re-evaluation to take place with full participation, i.e. with the participation of five judges, since initially only three of them voted.
If he fails here, he will seek a review of the proceedings by a higher authority, in this case the Supreme Court of the United States.
What is significant about the case is that the court omitted a document sent by the Mexican government as an amicus curiae unit detailing Vitro’s procedure under the Insolvency Act and pointing out that the company has made it easier for itself by resorting to agreements signed by the two countries.
In addition, it points out that the country has complied with the principles of the United Nations Commission on International Trade, i.e. the rules designed for international insolvency cases, which guarantee equality for both debtors and creditors.
