Hector "Hetin" Reyes: "Basketball was my life"
Basketball world champion Héctor "Hetin" Reyes has been associated with this indoor sport for more than 60 years and traveled the world thanks to it.
Few people in Puerto Rico have as many memories of the history of local basketball as Héctor "Hetin" Reyes.
Reyes had been involved in the sport for more than 60 years, whether as a junior player, BSN national basketball league player, owner and coach of Vaqueros de Bayamón in the national basketball league, or president of the Puerto Rican Basketball Federation.
“I have played many roles in basketball throughout my life, including several at the same time, such as when I was president of the BSN National League in the 1990s, national team chief executive and president of the federation,” Reyes recalled during a visit to the reporters of the newspaper Primera Hora at his home in Bayamón, where he has lived faithfully for more than 50 years with his husband, Isabel.
"Basketball was my life."
Reyes is not exaggerating.
The walls of his house, which are almost all decorated with photos and souvenirs from his long career, testify to this.
Bayamón in the heart
With the greatest movement of all, he guards those that commemorate his work at los Vaqueros from the mid-1950s, where he was a player until 1982, when he also celebrated 15 years as a co-owner or owner of the team.
“It was my best years, and I enjoyed it the most, because I had the opportunity to participate in eight championships with Los Vaqueros since 1967, whether as owner, co-owner or coach.
It was a series of successful years, including five championships held between 1971 and 1975.
And then I said goodbye to one championship - in 1981, when Jerome Mincy made his debut at BSN.
“The team was then taken over by Cuco Ortiz, who was an excellent leader,” Reyes said.
“I remember Gene Bartow, who was a former coach at the University of Alabama in Birmingham at the time, telling me, ‘I’ve got a big, two-meter-tall player for you.
Do you want it?"
And that was the beginning of Mincy, one of the best players Puerto Rico has ever had.
Bartow then recommended me a quarterback, Raymond Gausse, who became a member of the team and one of our top scorers.
I remember him saying that if Mincy brings Bayamone a championship win, then Gausse will contribute to the next one.”
The championship, when los Vaqueros played for Gausse, he enjoyed, but only at a distance, because in 1988 he was already the president of the basketball federation.
At that time, he wanted to devote himself fully to his functions and enjoy Mincy's placement in the national team.
“I remember the first time we beat the United States in the qualifying Olympics in Mexico in 1989.
“Then came the 1990 World Cup, where we finished in the quarter, but we should have had the bronze if it hadn’t been for the Canadian referee who let us repeat the final pitch,” Reyes said.
Is the 1990 World Cup team the best national team you’ve ever seen?
He is among the best, just like the one who beat the Dream Team at the 2004 Olympics.
But my favorite was the national team at the Pan American Games in Cuba in 1991, when we won gold and smashed the United States squad, which was quite similar to the one that blew us the bronze at the World Cup.
The team not only had Mincy, Gausse, Ramon Rivas, Fico López and "Piculina" (Ortiz), but also there were the youngsters (Javier) "Toñito" Colón and James Carter, brothers Leone (Francisco and Edgar) and Mario "Quijote" Morales, who could not be injured in the team round due to 1990.
The team that may not have had the perfect squad, but managed to win a gold medal and bring us great joy, was the team from the Olympic qualification in 1995 in Neuquén, Argentina.
With players on the roster such as "Canito" Nieves, Pablo Alicea and junior player Rolando Hourruitiner replacing players expelled due to a skirmish at the Pan American Games in Mar de Plata, we won gold against all predictions.
What was Puerto Rico’s best player?
It was no doubt Piculin Ortiz.
His numbers from international tournaments are impressive.
No one in Puerto Rico has achieved such results at this level as Piculin.
Not to mention his presence in the different leagues where he played.
Who was the best coach in Puerto Rico?
That's very difficult.
We had a very good generation, which includes Julio Toro, Flor Meléndez, Carlos Morales, Raymond Dalmau and Armando Torres.
I love the work of Leo Arilla.
What do you consider to be your greatest achievement in the federation?
That I was part of the most famous era of the national team from 1988 to 1995 and that in the early 1990s the national league had up to 17 teams in one season.
What didn't you have time to prove?
There were things I wanted to introduce, such as the division of youth categories by region.
For example, the Ponce boys would only play in their area and compete against teams from other corners of the island only in the national playoffs.
Now children travel a lot and play too many games, which is not necessary.
I also see benefits in compulsory certificates and courses for coaches, assistant referees and referees.
I'm glad to hear that.
What do you do now?
I mostly listen to music, watch YouTube videos with music from my time, enjoy my grandchildren and occasionally go to basketball games.
And of course, I enjoy the company of my wife, Isabel, who has always been by my side.
Actor Larry Hagman has died.
Larry Hagman, born September 21, 1931 in Forth Worth, Texas, was world-renowned for starring John Ross Ewing, better known as "J.R." in the television series Dallas, in which he embodied a man who acted recklessly and was insidious and manipulative.
Larry Hagman, whose role as predatory oil magnate J.R. Ewing in the television series Dallas became a symbol of greed in the 1980s, died.
He was 81 years old.
Hagman, who returned this year as J.R. in the new series of Dallas, died Friday afternoon of complications related to cancer, according to an official family announcement given to the Associated Press by Dallas production company Warner Bros.
"Larry has returned to his beloved hometown of Dallas, where he once again played the iconic role he loved most," the family said in a statement.
Larry's family and his closest friends were with him in Dallas for Thanksgiving.
“Linda Gray, who represented his wife in both the original and the new series, was with Hagman when he died at the Dallas hospital,” her agent Jeffrey Lane said in a statement.
He brought joy to everyone he knew.
"He was creative, generous, funny, kind, kind and talented, and I will miss him so much.
He was unique and lived his life to the fullest,” Linda Gray said in a statement.
Hagman was diagnosed with cirrhosis of the liver in 1992, and he admitted to drinking a lot for years.
In 1995, a malignant tumor was found on his liver, and Hagman underwent a transplant.
Years before the Dallas series aired, Hagman became famous on television as a decent guy in the lightweight comedy I Dream of Jeannie aired on NBC from 1965 to 1970.
Here he plays the character of Captain Tony Nelson, an astronaut whose life changes when he meets an attractive girl (a genie) played by Barbara Eden and takes her to his home to live together.
He also starred in two short-lived comedies, The Good Life (NBC, 1971–72) and Here We Go Again (ABC, 1973).
His appearances in the films included roles that were well received by critics: The Group, Harry and Tonto, and Primary Colors.
But it was Hangman's masterful performance in the form of the incredibly repulsive J.R. that led him to the stellar peak.
The CBS drama series about the Ewing clan and other personalities around them aired from April 1978 to May 1991.
The promotional slogan "Who Shot Jayar?", which was supposed to spark expectations about the emotion-filled work, when Hangman's character is nearly murdered, caused not only a huge amount of speculation from spectators around the world, but also a risk of millions of dollars in public offices.
This also helped this work to achieve a record in audience.
The November 1980 episode, in which the answer was revealed, was watched by an average of 41 million television viewers, making Dallas the second most watched entertainment show in history after the end of the 1983 MASH series, which was watched by 50 million viewers.
J.R. was shot by his sister-in-law Kristin (played by Mary Crosby).
Kristin got pregnant with J.R., and he threatened to label her a prostitute if she didn't leave town, but there were others who had reason to attack him.
Hagman played Ewing, a greedy greedy man with a charismatic smile: a crafty businessman and unfaithful husband who tried to keep his alcoholic wife Sue Ellen (Linda Gray) locked up in a medical facility.
"I know what I want J.R. to have on his tombstone," Hagman said in 1988.
It should say, "Here lies the honorary citizen J.R. Ewing."
That's the only thing that didn't work out.
Victoria Principal, who played in the original series, recalled Hagman on Friday as someone who was "great on and off the screen".
He is unforgettable and irreplaceable for millions of admirers in the world and in the hearts of all of us who have been fortunate enough to know and love him.
Ten episodes of the new Dallas series were broadcast by TNT a few months ago with great success.
"Five episodes of the second series have already been completed and the sixth is being filmed," the broadcaster said.
Immediately after Hangman's death, there was no statement from Warner or TNT about how the series would continue.
Born in Fort Worth, Texas, he was the son of actress and singer Mary Martin, who starred in classics such as the musicals South Pacific and Peter Pan.
Mary Martin was a very young girl when she gave birth to Larry in 1931, whose father was her husband, lawyer Ben Hagman.
In the early 1950s, Larry tried his luck on stage in New York City and then served in the Air Force in England from 1952 to 1956.
There he met a young Swedish designer, Maj Axelsson, whom he married.
The couple had two children, Preston and Heidi, and lived for a long time in the Californian city of Malibu, where many celebrities reside.
In 2001, he published his autobiographical book Hello Darlin': Tall (and Absolutely True) Tales about My Life.
"I didn't put anything in there that I knew could hurt someone or hurt them in any way," Asociado told the Prensa news agency.
After a liver transplant, he began to promote organ donation and worked as a volunteer in a hospital where he helped fearful patients.
"I advise them, I encourage them, I meet with them when they go into surgery and then afterwards," he said in 1996.
I'm trying to give them comfort in the sense of "don't worry, it's going to be a little uncomfortable for a while, but you'll be healthy."
He was also an anti-smoking activist and participated in various campaigns.
Starting a course that explores “the end of the world”
Every week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and bacteria, and global warming.
When religion professor Stuart Charmé decided to take a course on the end of the world this semester, he knew it was an irresistible enticement: The end of the “long count” of the Mayan calendar, due on December 21, caught many people’s attention as proof that the end of the world was coming.
Charmé had no idea what awaited him in the next few months: the catastrophic hurricane Sandy, the budgetary abyss that some call “Armageddon of debt,” and the growing conflict Israel is drawn into, the place where, according to end-of-the-world Christians, the Apocalypse begins.
"I didn't realize this was going to be the most apocalyptic semester ever," Charmé told students at Rutgers University in Camden, New Jersey, this week.
When you look at what’s going on in the world today as if you had 30 days left, it’s a really good time.
And remember, bad means good for the apocalyptic minded.
And this is not the only professor offering courses on "the end of the world" in this semester, which is theoretically the last in history.
At Temple University, Barry Vacker holds a course on "Means, Culture, and the End of the World".
Every week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and bacteria, and global warming.
“We’re discussing why these ideas spread over time,” he says, and how they offer hypothetical scenarios that drive certain human behavior.
For example, if nuclear material falls into the hands of terrorists, war could break out.
This month, students analyze movies with apocalyptic themes and explore how they differ from real-life examples.
“I’ve tried to inform students about what is possible, probable, believable and impossible,” says Vacker.
On the main campus of Pennsylvania State University, Matthew Restall, a professor of Latin American history, and his colleague Amara Solari, an assistant professor of art history and anthropology, came together to organize a course with the simple name The End of the World.
"We don't join 2012 because we always count on the possibility of taking a course again in case the world doesn't end," Restall said.
Despite the "threatening doom", students must study, create projects, and take final exams.
At Penn State, the final exam will take place on the eve of the Apocalypse, giving students no choice but to work "until the evening of the supposed end of the world," Restall said.
Courses have become quite popular.
"It stretched over two hours," Restall said of his course for high-average students, 35 of whom applied.
Weeks and weeks before the start of the semester, we received e-mails asking if there was still room.
The students themselves assure that the course is one of the most interesting.
“I find it fascinating to see what people do to comfort themselves,” Bridgid Robinson, a 23-year-old religious and sociological student from Haddonfield, New Jersey, said at Rutgers University in Camden.
Therefore, apocalyptic, secular, or religious thinking is only a matter of consolation or lack of it.
Will Wekesa, a 25-year-old student in the field of psychology and nursing, said he had seen all the apocalyptic movies.
"I've never heard of a class in which this could be taught before," he said.
"I'm enjoying it."
But no interviewed student, let alone a professor, said they believed in the end date of December 21.
"Our first project was about the Mayan predictions, and we're kind of refuting them," said Julie Zeglen, a 21-year-old senior student at West Chester's Temple University.
"The Mayans never predicted the end of the world; it's just a key point in the calendar," Restall said.
But he added that there is an apocalyptic anxiety in Western culture that dates back several centuries, with which people respond to changes in their surroundings with predictions of the end of the world.
The rise of this speculation was caused by the Internet.
"Jinde people don't think about it," he said.
This happens in the vast majority of the English-speaking world.
Joseph Dougherty, a professor of religion at La Salle University who lectures in the Philippines this year, responded quickly when asked if he knew of any "end of the world" course there.
“The Philippines is not taking part in the end of the world,” he wrote, pointing to an exception at the highest office.
We have grace from the Pope.
Restall noted that over the years, many days of judgment have been talked about, and said that if nothing happens on December 21, "people will immediately start thinking about the next date" or philosophizing that December 21 is the beginning of a seven-year period at the end of which the world will disappear.
The date is taken lightly by students and professors.
Several said they intend to go to the "end of the world" festivities.
"I'll probably call a few friends to laugh together," said Samira Ford, a 20-year-old communications student.
